# Circular Arc Profile

If you look at the Hot Apple Pie box, it looks like a circular arc for the flap profile:

![Flat box](images/Clean_flat.jpg)

So how well does a circular arc work?

## Volcabulary

From [the internet](https:aplutopper.com)

![parts of a circle](images/parts_of_a_circle.png)


## Setup

![](images/arc.png)

* Consider this *sector* with an angle \\(-{\theta}\_0\leq\theta\leq\{\theta}\_0\\)
* *Radius* \\(R\\)
* The unfolded dimension along the *chord* is
\\[s(\theta)=R \sin(\theta)\quad -R \sin({\theta}\_0)\leq s \leq R \sin({\theta}\_0)\\]
* Width is the length of the *chord*
\\[W=2 R \sin({\theta}\_0)\\]
* The curve is the *arc* 
\\[f(s(\theta))=R \cos(\theta) - R \cos({\theta}\_0)\\]
* Maximum curve height
\\[f\_{max}=R (1-\cos({\theta}\_0)\leq L\\]
* Curve *tangent* (derivative)
\\[f'(s)=\frac{\frac{d f}{d \theta}}{\frac{d s}{d \theta}}=- \tan(\theta)\\]
* Constraint that \\(\lvert f'\rvert \leq 1\\) implies
\\[0\leq{\theta}\_0\leq\pi/4\\]

## Normalize \\(W=1\\)

* *Radius*
\\[R=\frac{1}{2 \sin({\theta}\_0)}\\]
* *Chord* coordinate
\\[s=\frac{\sin(\theta)}{2 \sin({\theta}\_0)}\quad -1/2\leq s \leq 1/2\\]
\\[d s=\frac{\cos(\theta)}{2 \sin({\theta}\_0)} d \theta\\]
* *Arc*
\\[f(s)=\frac{\cos(\theta)}{2 \sin({\theta}\_0)}-\frac{\cos({\theta}\_0)}{2 \sin({\theta}\_0)}\\]
\\[f'(s)=\frac{d f}{d s}=- \frac{\sin(\theta)}{\cos(\theta)}\\]

## Folded (normalized)


\\[d x=\sqrt{1-f'\^2} d s= \frac{\sqrt{\cos\^2(\theta)-\sin\^2(\theta)}}{2 \sin({\theta}\_0)} d \theta\\]
\\[z=f(s)=\frac{\cos(\theta)}{2 \sin({\theta}\_0)}-\frac{\cos({\theta}\_0)}{2 \sin({\theta}\_0)}\\]
\\[y=L-f(s)=L-\frac{\cos(\theta)}{2 \sin({\theta}\_0)}+\frac{\cos({\theta}\_0)}{2 \sin({\theta}\_0)}\\]

*Note we are using a normalized \\(L=\frac{OldL}{2 \sin({\theta}\_0)}\\)*

## Volume

Our expression for Volume:

\\[V=4 \int f\times(L-f) d x\\]

Or using \\(\theta\\) parametrically and recognizing that there is symmetry in \\(\pm\theta\\):

\\[V=\frac{8}{2\^3 \sin\^3({\theta}\_0)} \int\_0\^{{\theta}\_0} \lbrace\cos(\theta)-\cos({\theta}\_0)\rbrace \lbrace L-\cos(\theta)+\cos({\theta}\_0)\rbrace\sqrt{\cos\^2(\theta)-\sin\^2(\theta)}\\,d \theta\\]

The integral can be evaluated numerically, but is not resolvable in elementary functions.

## Maxima

We can try to find conditions for maximum volume for arc profiles.

\\[V = \int\_0\^{{\theta}\_0} F(\theta,{\theta}\_0,L) d \theta\quad \text{where}\\, F(\theta,{\theta}\_0,L)=\frac{\lbrace\cos(\theta)-\cos({\theta}\_0)\rbrace \lbrace L-\cos(\theta)+\cos({\theta}\_0)\rbrace\sqrt{\cos\^2(\theta)-\sin\^2(\theta)}}{\sin\^3({\theta}\_0)}\\]

### Length

\\[\frac{\partial V}{\partial L}=0=\int\_0\^{{\theta}\_0}\frac{\cos(\theta)-\cos({\theta}\_0)}{sin\^3({\theta}\_0)}\sqrt{\cos\^2(\theta)-sin\^2(\theta)}\\,d \theta\\]
\\[\int\_0\^{{\theta}\_0}\frac{\cos(\theta)-\cos({\theta}\_0)}{sin\^3({\theta}\_0)}\sqrt{\cos\^2(\theta)-sin\^2(\theta)}\\,d \theta=0\\]
\\[\int\_0\^{{\theta}\_0}\lbrace\cos(\theta)-\cos({\theta}\_0)\rbrace\sqrt{\cos\^2(\theta)-sin\^2(\theta)}\\,d \theta=0\\]

In the range \\(0\leq\theta\leq\pi/4\\) both terms are positive, so the integral is never 0. Indeed:
\\[\lim\_{L\rightarrow\infty} V=\infty\\]

### Angle \\({\theta}\_0\\)

\\[\frac{\partial V}{\partial {\theta}\_0}=0= F({\theta}\_0,{\theta}\_0,L)-\int\_0\^{{\theta}\_0} F(\theta,{\theta}\_0,L) \\,d \theta\\]
The first term is from integral limit being the dependent on \\({\theta}\_0\\), but
\\[\text{Note:}\quad F({\theta}\_0,{\theta}\_0,L)=0\\]

\\[\int\_0\^{{\theta}\_0}\frac{\cos\^3({\theta}\_0)+2 \cos({\theta}\_0)-2 \cos(\theta)\lbrace 2  \cos\^2({\theta}\_0)+1\rbrace+3 \cos\^2(\theta) \cos({\theta}\_0)-L \lbrace 3 \cos(\theta) \cos({\theta}\_0)+2 \cos\^2({\theta}\_0)+1\rbrace}{\sin\^4({\theta}\_{0})}\sqrt{\cos\^2(\theta)-\sin\^2(\theta)}\\,d \theta=0 
\\]